\section{Multiple Choice}

Multiple-choice questions carry the prompt, the offered options, and whether
the form should use radio buttons or checkboxes.  We require at least one
option so the later rendering and counting logic can rely on the list being
non-empty.

<<classes>>=
@dataclass(frozen=True)
class MCQuestion:
    """A multiple-choice question."""

    text: str
    options: tuple[str, ...]
    multi: bool = False
    kind: str = "mc"

    def __post_init__(self):
        if not self.options:
            raise ValueError("multiple-choice questions need options")

    def to_dict(self) -> dict[str, Any]:
        """Return a JSON-friendly representation of the question."""

        return {
            "kind": self.kind,
            "text": self.text,
            "options": list(self.options),
            "multi": self.multi,
        }
@

Let's verify that the constructor rejects the degenerate case with no options:

<<test functions>>=
def test_mc_question_requires_options():
    with pytest.raises(ValueError):
        MCQuestion("Which one?", ())
@

\section{Open Questions}

Open questions need the prompt and a character limit, and they can optionally
carry a markdown fence language for uploaded file bodies.  The limit belongs to
the question data because it affects both the HTTP form and the canonical hash.
The fence hint also belongs here, but it has to be a single CommonMark info word:
whitespace or backticks would change the structure of the generated fence rather
than just its language tag.  We omit the hint from the canonical JSON when it is
unset so existing open-question hashes stay byte-for-byte stable.

<<classes>>=
@dataclass(frozen=True)
class OpenQuestion:
    """An open-text question with a character cap.

    The optional fence language tags uploaded file bodies as
    fenced Markdown.
    """

    text: str
    max_chars: int = 280
    fence: str | None = None
    kind: str = "open"

    <<open question methods>>
@

\subsection{Validation}

The open-question validation has two independent invariants.  The character
limit protects the form and storage layers from an impossible input contract,
while the fence check protects Markdown rendering from turning a language hint
into fence structure.

<<open question methods>>=
def __post_init__(self):
    <<validate open question limit>>
    <<validate open question fence>>
@

The length cap must be positive because both the HTML form and answer recorder
treat it as an actual upper bound.

<<validate open question limit>>=
if self.max_chars <= 0:
    raise ValueError("open questions need a positive character limit")
@

The fence language is optional, but when present it must be one CommonMark info
word.  Whitespace or backticks would change the syntax of the generated fenced
block, not merely its label.

<<validate open question fence>>=
if self.fence is not None and (
    not self.fence or any(char.isspace() or char == "`" for char in self.fence)
):
    raise ValueError(
        "markdown fence language must be a non-empty word "
        "without whitespace or backticks"
    )
