\section{Word Clouds}

A word-cloud question looks like an open question on the way in: respondents
type free text into a single field.  The way out is different.  Instead of
listing the answers verbatim, the results page aggregates them into a
frequency map that a renderer turns into a cloud, a sized list, or a plain
table.

That asymmetry shapes the data model.  We split a word-cloud's fields into
two layers.  The \emph{identity} layer is the prompt and the character
limit --- the parts that shape the input contract a respondent sees.
Everything else --- splitting mode, minimum word length, stop-word
configuration, render mode --- is \emph{presentation}.  Only the identity
layer enters the canonical hash, so a lecturer can switch between an SVG
cloud and a frequency table without inventing a new question identifier
and orphaning the answers already collected.  This is a stronger guarantee
than the open question's optional fence, which still alters the hash when
set: for a word cloud, the visualisation never changes the identity.

<<classes>>=
@dataclass(frozen=True)
class WordCloudQuestion:
    """A free-text question whose results aggregate into a word cloud.

    The visualisation fields (``split_words``, ``min_word_length``,
    ``extra_stop_words``, ``use_default_stopwords``, ``render``) are
    presentation hints: they do not affect the question's canonical
    identity, so editing them and recompiling preserves the existing
    answer pool.
    """

    text: str
    max_chars: int = 280
    split_words: bool = True
    min_word_length: int = 3
    extra_stop_words: tuple[str, ...] = ()
    use_default_stopwords: bool = True
    render: str = "svg"
    kind: str = "wordcloud"

    <<wordcloud question methods>>
@

\subsection{Validation}

Each presentation field has its own invariant.  Checking them at
construction means a misconfigured slide source fails when the document is
compiled, not when the first respondent reaches the results page.

<<wordcloud question methods>>=
def __post_init__(self):
    <<validate wordcloud limit>>
    <<validate wordcloud min length>>
    <<validate wordcloud render mode>>
