The character limit is the only field shared with [[OpenQuestion]], and it
carries the same input-contract meaning: the HTTP form and the answer
recorder both treat it as a real upper bound, so a non-positive value
would let the storage layer accept an answer the form refuses.

<<validate wordcloud limit>>=
if self.max_chars <= 0:
    raise ValueError(
        "word-cloud questions need a positive character limit"
    )
@

The minimum word length defaults to three, which is large enough to drop
single-character pronouns and the two-letter copulas that dominate an
English cloud without revealing anything (\enquote{is}, \enquote{do},
\enquote{it}).  Zero is a legitimate value (\enquote{keep every token}),
so the bound only rejects negative thresholds.

<<validate wordcloud min length>>=
if self.min_word_length < 0:
    raise ValueError(
        "word-cloud minimum word length must be non-negative"
    )
@

The render mode names one of three rendering paths that the server and
CLI implement.  Validating it eagerly catches typos in the slide source
at compile time; otherwise an invalid value would only fail when the
first respondent loads the results page.

<<validate wordcloud render mode>>=
if self.render not in ("svg", "scaled", "table"):
    raise ValueError(
        "word-cloud render must be one of "
        "'svg', 'scaled', or 'table'; "
        f"got {self.render!r}"
    )
@

The character-limit check is the same invariant the open question
relies on, so we pin it explicitly to keep the two question types in
agreement about what a valid input contract looks like.

<<test functions>>=
def test_word_cloud_question_requires_positive_limit():
    with pytest.raises(ValueError):
        WordCloudQuestion("Topic?", max_chars=0)
