\subsection{Serialisation}

A word-cloud serialises into two different dictionaries depending on what
the caller needs.  [[to_dict]] returns the full persistence shape: it is
what the store writes to disk so a future render can recover the same
configuration.  [[canonical_dict]] returns identity only --- prompt and
character limit --- so two visualisations of the same prompt hash to the
same identifier and share the same answer pool.

<<wordcloud question methods>>=
def to_dict(self) -> dict[str, Any]:
    """Return the full persistence shape of the question."""

    return {
        "kind": self.kind,
        "text": self.text,
        "max_chars": self.max_chars,
        "split_words": self.split_words,
        "min_word_length": self.min_word_length,
        "extra_stop_words": list(self.extra_stop_words),
        "use_default_stopwords": self.use_default_stopwords,
        "render": self.render,
    }

def canonical_dict(self) -> dict[str, Any]:
    """Return the identity-only shape used by ``question_hash``."""

    return {
        "kind": self.kind,
        "text": self.text,
        "max_chars": self.max_chars,
    }
@

The persistence round-trip pins that every configuration knob survives a
trip through JSON.  We list the stop words as a sequence because JSON has
no tuple, then check that the rebuilt question still hashes to a tuple
internally --- the frozen dataclass would otherwise refuse to compare
equal after reload.

<<test functions>>=

def test_word_cloud_to_dict_includes_all_fields():
    question = WordCloudQuestion(
        "Words?",
        max_chars=140,
        split_words=False,
        min_word_length=4,
        extra_stop_words=("foo", "bar"),
        use_default_stopwords=False,
        render="table",
    )

    assert question.to_dict() == {
        "kind": "wordcloud",
        "text": "Words?",
        "max_chars": 140,
        "split_words": False,
        "min_word_length": 4,
        "extra_stop_words": ["foo", "bar"],
        "use_default_stopwords": False,
        "render": "table",
    }
@

The canonical dictionary is the central guarantee of this question type:
no matter how the presentation evolves, two word clouds with the same
prompt and character limit share an identity.

<<test functions>>=

def test_word_cloud_canonical_dict_excludes_presentation_fields():
