\subsection{Counting tokens}

The frequency method is the contract between the question and its
renderers.  Each of the three render modes (SVG, scaled list, table)
consumes the same descending-by-count sequence of (word, count) pairs,
so the filter behaviour lives on the question rather than being
duplicated in every renderer.

Splitting walks each answer once.  In split mode we first replace every
Unicode punctuation character with a space, then casefold and split on
whitespace.  Replacing rather than stripping is what lets
\enquote{café—café} count as two cafés and \enquote{don't} count as
\enquote{don} --- if we stripped instead, the em-dash variant would
collapse into a single \enquote{cafécafé} token that no one wrote.  We
use [[unicodedata.category]] rather than [[string.punctuation]] because
the latter is ASCII-only and would miss the en-dash and the curly
apostrophes Swedish answers tend to contain.  Tokens that fall below
the minimum length or that match the active stop-word set are
discarded; the rest accumulate into a frequency counter.  In
whole-answer mode each non-empty stripped answer counts as one
token --- useful when the prompt asks for a single phrase rather than
free prose.

The final sort is descending by count, then ascending by word.  The
secondary key makes the output deterministic when several words tie ---
which the renderers rely on to lay out a stable cloud.

<<wordcloud question methods>>=
def frequencies(
    self, answers: Iterable[Mapping[str, Any]]
) -> list[tuple[str, int]]:
    """Return ``(word, count)`` pairs sorted by descending count.

    Ties are broken alphabetically by word so that renderers
    consuming the sequence lay out a deterministic cloud.
    """

    counter: Counter[str] = Counter()
    stops = self._effective_stop_words()
    for answer in answers:
        text = str(answer.get("value", ""))
        if self.split_words:
            normalized = _punctuation_to_space(text).casefold()
            for word in normalized.split():
                if (
                    len(word) >= self.min_word_length
                    and word not in stops
                ):
                    counter[word] += 1
        else:
            token = text.strip()
            if token:
                counter[token] += 1
    return sorted(
        counter.items(), key=lambda pair: (-pair[1], pair[0])
    )

def _effective_stop_words(self) -> frozenset[str]:
    extra = frozenset(word.casefold() for word in self.extra_stop_words)
    if self.use_default_stopwords:
        return DEFAULT_STOP_WORDS | extra
    return extra
@

The punctuation replacer lives at module scope because the splitter is
the only caller that needs it and the operation is purely textual ---
keeping it off the dataclass keeps the question API focused on what
authors actually configure.  We map punctuation to a single space
rather than the empty string so that, when an en-dash separates two
words, the splitter sees two tokens rather than a concatenation of
them.

<<functions>>=
def _punctuation_to_space(text: str) -> str:
    return "".join(
        " " if unicodedata.category(char).startswith("P") else char
        for char in text
    )
@

The split-mode happy path doubles as the contract test: lowercase,
short-token, and stop-word filters all apply, and ties break by ascending
word.

<<test functions>>=

def test_word_cloud_frequencies_splits_lowercases_and_filters():
    question = WordCloudQuestion("Topic?")
    answers = [
        {"value": "Apple apple BANANA"},
        {"value": "banana orange"},
        {"value": "is do I"},  # all filtered: short or stop-word
    ]

    assert question.frequencies(answers) == [
        ("apple", 2),
        ("banana", 2),
        ("orange", 1),
    ]
@

Whole-answer mode skips the splitter entirely and counts each non-empty
stripped response.  Authors use it when the prompt is a single-word poll
(\enquote{Pick one word that describes today}).

<<test functions>>=

def test_word_cloud_frequencies_whole_answer_mode():
    question = WordCloudQuestion("Topic?", split_words=False)
    answers = [
        {"value": "Linear algebra"},
        {"value": "linear algebra"},
        {"value": "  Linear algebra  "},
        {"value": ""},
    ]

    counts = dict(question.frequencies(answers))

    assert counts["Linear algebra"] == 2
    assert counts["linear algebra"] == 1
@

Unicode punctuation needs an explicit test because [[string.punctuation]]
would miss the very characters that hurt Swedish answers --- the
en-dash and the curly apostrophe.  Replacing punctuation with a space
also means an apostrophe in \enquote{don't} splits the token; the
residual \enquote{t} is then dropped for being shorter than the
minimum length, leaving the meaningful stem in the cloud.

<<test functions>>=

def test_word_cloud_frequencies_strips_unicode_punctuation():
    question = WordCloudQuestion("Topic?")
    answers = [
        {"value": "café—café"},      # em-dash between words
        {"value": "don’t can’t"},  # curly apostrophes
    ]

    counts = dict(question.frequencies(answers))

    assert counts["café"] == 2
    assert counts["don"] == 1
    assert counts["can"] == 1
@

Extra stop words extend the built-in list when [[use_default_stopwords]]
is true, and replace it entirely when false.  Both behaviours matter ---
the union covers the common case, the replacement covers a course that
wants the cloud to keep \enquote{the} and \enquote{is}.

The first scenario covers the common case: a course-specific stop-word
list extends the built-ins.  An answer of \enquote{python python ruby}
should reduce to a single \enquote{ruby} count once the author tells
the question to ignore \enquote{python}.

<<test functions>>=

def test_word_cloud_frequencies_applies_extra_stop_words():
    question = WordCloudQuestion(
        "Topic?", extra_stop_words=("python",)
    )

    counts = dict(question.frequencies(
        [{"value": "python python ruby"}]
    ))

    assert "python" not in counts
    assert counts["ruby"] == 1
@

The second scenario covers the rarer but legitimate case where a
lecturer wants to keep what we would normally filter out --- for
example, a linguistics class studying article usage in student writing.
Turning the defaults off must let \enquote{the} resurface, so we drop
the minimum length to one and check that the built-in entry is gone
from the active set.

<<test functions>>=

def test_word_cloud_frequencies_disables_default_stopwords():
    question = WordCloudQuestion(
        "Topic?",
        use_default_stopwords=False,
        min_word_length=1,
    )

    counts = dict(question.frequencies(
        [{"value": "the the cat"}]
    ))

    assert counts["the"] == 2
    assert counts["cat"] == 1
