The word-cloud invariance test pins the central guarantee of the new
question type.  A lecturer who iterates on visualisation must not lose
the answers already collected, which only holds if presentation choices
never change the hash.  We deliberately vary several presentation
fields at once: any one of them slipping into the canonical payload
would break this assertion.

<<test functions>>=

def test_question_hash_invariant_to_word_cloud_presentation_changes():
    base = WordCloudQuestion("Words?", max_chars=200)
    variants = [
        WordCloudQuestion("Words?", max_chars=200, render="table"),
        WordCloudQuestion("Words?", max_chars=200, split_words=False),
        WordCloudQuestion("Words?", max_chars=200, min_word_length=5),
        WordCloudQuestion(
            "Words?", max_chars=200, extra_stop_words=("foo",)
        ),
        WordCloudQuestion(
            "Words?", max_chars=200, use_default_stopwords=False
        ),
    ]

    digest = question_hash(base)
    for variant in variants:
        assert question_hash(variant) == digest
@

Conversely, changing the identity fields must still change the digest
--- otherwise two genuinely different prompts would collide on the same
URL prefix.

<<test functions>>=

def test_question_hash_changes_when_word_cloud_identity_changes():
    base = WordCloudQuestion("Words?", max_chars=200)

    assert question_hash(base) != question_hash(
        WordCloudQuestion("Other words?", max_chars=200)
    )
    assert question_hash(base) != question_hash(
        WordCloudQuestion("Words?", max_chars=140)
    )
